WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.784 --> 00:00:10.450
NARRATION BY SYLVESTER
MCCOY: There once

00:00:10.450 --> 00:00:17.400
was a clever and passionate girl
who wondered away from a fair.

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:21.370
She ventured inside
a wagon-like ride,

00:00:21.370 --> 00:00:23.615
and what did she find in there?

00:00:27.550 --> 00:00:37.280
"The Squickerwonkers."

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:41.790
Welcome my dears said
a voice from the winds,

00:00:41.790 --> 00:00:47.650
to the fabulous squicker show.

00:00:47.650 --> 00:00:55.060
You dropped in your coin,
so now you can join.

00:00:55.060 --> 00:00:59.760
Come up here and
see how it goes.

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:03.840
The girl looked
around to see who

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:07.660
it was that spoke
with a sinister tone.

00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:12.200
But she saw not a soul
save a rat and old.

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:14.297
It seemed that the
girl was alone.

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:21.280
And once there came
a noise from above,

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:25.770
nine figures swung
down from the shadows.

00:01:25.770 --> 00:01:29.790
Their bodies hung loose
as a strung from a noose

00:01:29.790 --> 00:01:32.568
as if all nine were
hanging from gallows.

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:39.290
Come on to the stage.

00:01:39.290 --> 00:01:40.910
Don't be afraid.

00:01:40.910 --> 00:01:44.090
Meet my motley crew.

00:01:44.090 --> 00:01:48.260
They may have their vices
but those are my spices

00:01:48.260 --> 00:01:51.446
and I suspect so do you.

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:58.450
The head of the
Squickerwonker troop

00:01:58.450 --> 00:02:01.111
is known as Papa the Proud.

00:02:01.111 --> 00:02:02.110
MARK DOUGLAS: All right.

00:02:02.110 --> 00:02:04.484
That was a little bit
of "Squickerwonkers"

00:02:04.484 --> 00:02:06.900
by Evangeline Lilly, and that
was actually her reading it,

00:02:06.900 --> 00:02:08.270
which I was really
impressed that she

00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:09.479
could do that with her voice.

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:10.810
Ladies and gentlemen,
if you could please

00:02:10.810 --> 00:02:11.643
give a warm welcome.

00:02:11.643 --> 00:02:16.330
You know her as "Freckles"
aka Kate from "Lost," Tauriel

00:02:16.330 --> 00:02:18.870
from "The Hobbit," and she just
finished filming "Ant Man,"

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:19.940
I believe.

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:21.400
She's the queen of comic con.

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.030
Give it up for Evangeline Lilly.

00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:33.350
EVANGELINE LILLY: You
have awesome hair.

00:02:33.350 --> 00:02:35.340
Awesome hair.

00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:38.620
I expected everyone at Google
to have awesome hair like that.

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:40.414
So many of you are
so much more boring

00:02:40.414 --> 00:02:41.580
than I thought you would be.

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:42.417
TODD WOMACK: Come on,
give them a chance.

00:02:42.417 --> 00:02:42.490
Give them a chance.

00:02:42.490 --> 00:02:43.400
MARK DOUGLAS: Wow.

00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:45.070
Way to insult the audience
right out of the gate.

00:02:45.070 --> 00:02:45.243
EVANGELINE LILLY: All right.

00:02:45.243 --> 00:02:46.120
But wait.

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:47.417
You guys are amazing.

00:02:47.417 --> 00:02:50.399
I'm so happy to
be here at Google.

00:02:50.399 --> 00:02:51.483
TODD WOMACK: There you go.

00:02:51.483 --> 00:02:52.523
EVANGELINE LILLY: Google.

00:02:52.523 --> 00:02:53.858
G-O-O-G-L-E. You know G.

00:02:53.858 --> 00:02:56.610
TODD WOMACK: Dot com.

00:02:56.610 --> 00:02:59.070
MARK DOUGLAS: I was trying
to get a feel for it.

00:02:59.070 --> 00:02:59.770
I was there.

00:02:59.770 --> 00:03:00.730
I was with you.

00:03:00.730 --> 00:03:01.641
This is on right?

00:03:01.641 --> 00:03:02.140
Hello?

00:03:02.140 --> 00:03:02.640
OK.

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:03.560
Good.

00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:05.614
TODD WOMACK: Who did
the voice over for that?

00:03:05.614 --> 00:03:08.030
EVANGELINE LILLY: That was the
incredible Sylvester McCoy.

00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:10.540
Some of you might know
him from Doctor Who.

00:03:10.540 --> 00:03:13.580
And he was Radagast
in "The Hobbit."

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:14.599
He did an amazing job.

00:03:14.599 --> 00:03:16.640
TODD WOMACK: You really
brought out the big guns.

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:19.420
I mean, Peter Jackson
did the forward

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:21.760
to this book and Fran
Walsh and Philippa Boyens

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:23.471
who basically write the movies.

00:03:23.471 --> 00:03:24.970
EVANGELINE LILLY:
I was lucky enough

00:03:24.970 --> 00:03:27.365
to be hanging out with big
guns when I made the movie,

00:03:27.365 --> 00:03:30.090
so on their downtime, they'd
invite me over for dinner,

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:32.580
and I'd be like, you want
to just look at this?

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:33.200
I just brought something over.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:34.710
It just happened
to be in my purse.

00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:36.380
And then they were
wonderful enough

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:38.550
to give me their
feedback and input

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:40.540
and actually Fran Walsh
and Philippa Boyens

00:03:40.540 --> 00:03:42.720
worked tirelessly with me.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:46.550
They had no extra time,
but they spent ours

00:03:46.550 --> 00:03:48.280
helping me edit the
book and make it

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:49.280
everything it should be.

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:53.130
Because I initially wrote
the story when I was 14,

00:03:53.130 --> 00:03:56.710
and it wasn't the poem
that exists in this book.

00:03:56.710 --> 00:03:59.890
I had to go through a ton of
rewrites to make it publishable

00:03:59.890 --> 00:04:01.970
and make it something
they would essentially

00:04:01.970 --> 00:04:04.960
introduce a series of 18 books.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:05.970
MARK DOUGLAS: Oh, wow.

00:04:05.970 --> 00:04:08.049
TODD WOMACK: So that
leads us to, well,

00:04:08.049 --> 00:04:09.590
I guess we've gotten
to get a picture

00:04:09.590 --> 00:04:13.184
from the VO and the audio what
kind of the piece is about.

00:04:13.184 --> 00:04:14.475
MARK DOUGLAS: The general tone.

00:04:14.475 --> 00:04:17.360
It's much scarier that way.

00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:18.225
I was like, ooh.

00:04:18.225 --> 00:04:19.600
EVANGELINE LILLY:
I just recently

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:21.350
was that the Brooklyn
Library, and I

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:23.940
started by asking the kids in
the audience, how many of you

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:26.130
have read the book,
and almost everyone

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:27.670
had because we had
prepped the kids.

00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:30.130
And then basically--

00:04:30.130 --> 00:04:33.400
MARK DOUGLAS: Did your
teacher make you read it?

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:37.350
EVANGELINE LILLY: And did she
tell you to say you love it?

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:38.850
TODD WOMACK: What
age were the kids?

00:04:38.850 --> 00:04:39.910
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Second graders,

00:04:39.910 --> 00:04:41.400
impossible to
control, by the way.

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:42.900
Second graders are crazy.

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:44.717
But I asked them was a scary?

00:04:44.717 --> 00:04:46.300
Did you guys think
the book was scary?

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:49.250
And they were all like
no, it's not scary.

00:04:49.250 --> 00:04:50.380
We're so tough.

00:04:50.380 --> 00:04:52.760
And then I did it this
way with the audio

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:55.086
and I actually read it
instead of Sylvester.

00:04:55.086 --> 00:04:58.720
And like I could tell that
within the second or third

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:01.410
page, they were all like,
I'm kind of scared now.

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:05.045
TODD WOMACK: They're like
this is lady is nuts.

00:05:05.045 --> 00:05:07.420
EVANGELINE LILLY: I don't know
if it was me or the music.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:10.070
MARK DOUGLAS: Mommy, why is the
pretty lady freaking us out?

00:05:10.070 --> 00:05:11.620
EVANGELINE LILLY: Oh,
speaking of pretty lady.

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:12.840
It was the cutest
thing in the world.

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:14.560
There was this little
boy in the front row.

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:17.226
I mean, it was like, if you were
the little boy in the front row

00:05:17.226 --> 00:05:19.160
and he sat there
through the whole thing.

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:22.480
It was so distracting and
he just kept doing this,

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:23.655
you are so beautiful.

00:05:26.597 --> 00:05:28.930
I was wearing bright red
lipstick that day and you know,

00:05:28.930 --> 00:05:30.720
little kids are suckers
for bright red lipstick.

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:31.490
TODD WOMACK: Are they?

00:05:31.490 --> 00:05:33.781
MARK DOUGLAS: I think there's
a couple guys up here who

00:05:33.781 --> 00:05:36.360
are fighting the urge
to say that right now.

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:39.617
You were talking about big
guns, speaking of guns,

00:05:39.617 --> 00:05:40.450
like what do you do?

00:05:40.450 --> 00:05:42.699
TODD WOMACK: Why did you
bring out the big guns today?

00:05:42.699 --> 00:05:45.070
MARK DOUGLAS: Was it just
all that bow and arrow work?

00:05:45.070 --> 00:05:46.100
EVANGELINE LILLY: No.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:48.270
I mean, everyone
is always like so

00:05:48.270 --> 00:05:51.600
what did you get a trainer
and all that stuff for roles,

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:53.500
and I don't do
any of that stuff.

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:55.249
I'm the laziest fit
person in the world.

00:05:55.249 --> 00:05:57.290
TODD WOMACK: Do you do
like the "Rocky IV" thing?

00:05:57.290 --> 00:06:00.220
MARK DOUGLAS: What is
the secret to that?

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:01.750
because I got the
lazy part down.

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:03.450
EVANGELINE LILLY:
The secret to that

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:06.630
is that for a good
10 years of my life,

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:09.670
I was obsessed with fitness.

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:12.000
So there's a lot of
muscle memory in here.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:15.440
So like now like
since I had a kid,

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:17.100
there's just not
so much time for it

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:18.720
or nearly as much
passion for it.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:20.610
But there was a
period in my life

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:22.700
where I would be the
person in the gym

00:06:22.700 --> 00:06:24.830
for like two or three
hours at a time.

00:06:24.830 --> 00:06:27.032
MARK DOUGLAS: In one day.

00:06:27.032 --> 00:06:27.990
EVANGELINE LILLY: Yeah.

00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:28.950
Sometimes twice a day.

00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:30.140
MARK DOUGLAS: I do
that over a month.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:30.544
EVANGELINE LILLY: I loved it.

00:06:30.544 --> 00:06:31.460
I loved it for awhile.

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:34.120
MARK DOUGLAS: But this is
really, this is your passion.

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:36.120
Is this kind of an
area that you want

00:06:36.120 --> 00:06:38.345
to go in more so
than acting even.

00:06:38.345 --> 00:06:42.480
EVANGELINE LILLY: Well, for
anybody who is in any way,

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:45.090
shape or form a fan of mine,
they probably know that

00:06:45.090 --> 00:06:47.690
I'm kind of vocal about
the fact that I'm not--

00:06:47.690 --> 00:06:49.230
I don't love acting and it's--

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:50.110
MARK DOUGLAS: What?

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:51.950
EVANGELINE LILLY: I know.

00:06:51.950 --> 00:06:55.260
Every struggling actress out
there just wants to lynch me.

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:58.630
They probably hate my guts,
but it just sort of happened,

00:06:58.630 --> 00:07:00.990
and I got lucky, and
this thing happened,

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:03.860
and I was sort of taken aback
by it, and I didn't love it.

00:07:03.860 --> 00:07:05.932
It wasn't for me
really, and so I've

00:07:05.932 --> 00:07:08.265
continued to do it because
it's a pretty decent day job.

00:07:08.265 --> 00:07:08.790
It pays OK.

00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:09.790
TODD WOMACK: Not to bad.

00:07:09.790 --> 00:07:09.980
Yeah.

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:10.320
Yeah.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:11.380
EVANGELINE LILLY:
But in the meantime,

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:13.150
I've been working
very hard on pursuing

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:15.220
my actual dream and
my actual passion,

00:07:15.220 --> 00:07:16.970
which is to be a writer.

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:21.550
In fact, in the last
let's see five years,

00:07:21.550 --> 00:07:24.980
I have spent a year and
three months acting,

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:29.396
and I have spent the rest of
the time, full time as a writer.

00:07:29.396 --> 00:07:32.020
MARK DOUGLAS: But it was kind of
interesting for somebody who's

00:07:32.020 --> 00:07:34.930
not crazy about acting, you're
in some pretty cool stuff.

00:07:34.930 --> 00:07:36.020
EVANGELINE LILLY: I know.

00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:36.390
Isn't that great?

00:07:36.390 --> 00:07:38.332
MARK DOUGLAS: I mean,
but it's kind of nice.

00:07:38.332 --> 00:07:39.790
You don't have to
feel the pressure

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:43.292
like take every like
girlfriend part, or you know?

00:07:43.292 --> 00:07:45.630
You get to do some
really cool stuff.

00:07:45.630 --> 00:07:48.110
I mean like, "Ant Man,"
I mean, do you just

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:52.020
have nerds camping out
in your front yard?

00:07:52.020 --> 00:07:54.650
EVANGELINE LILLY:
You know, what's

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:59.100
wonderful is I sort of come to
the promised land of geekdom

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:00.730
because I was--

00:08:00.730 --> 00:08:03.210
MARK DOUGLAS: You're at
the very core of it now.

00:08:03.210 --> 00:08:04.992
EVANGELINE LILLY:
I found my people.

00:08:04.992 --> 00:08:07.200
TODD WOMACK: These people
are working on their phones

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:08.600
while they're listening.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:10.190
That's how geeky we are.

00:08:10.190 --> 00:08:12.190
EVANGELINE LILLY: They're
20%-ing right now.

00:08:12.190 --> 00:08:15.512
TODD WOMACK: Oh, look at that,
throwing around the lingo.

00:08:15.512 --> 00:08:16.470
EVANGELINE LILLY: Yeah.

00:08:16.470 --> 00:08:16.970
I know.

00:08:16.970 --> 00:08:20.360
I was not like the
cool girl in school.

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:22.390
I broke the--

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:24.635
TODD WOMACK: Was
that your opinion?

00:08:24.635 --> 00:08:25.510
EVANGELINE LILLY: No.

00:08:25.510 --> 00:08:25.657
For real.

00:08:25.657 --> 00:08:26.590
TODD WOMACK: You
grew up in Canada.

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:27.330
EVANGELINE LILLY: I did.

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:27.829
I did.

00:08:27.829 --> 00:08:33.150
And I will admittedly say that
because the cool girls didn't

00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:36.799
want a pretty girl wandering
around that was outside

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:39.419
of their core, because
that's a threat,

00:08:39.419 --> 00:08:43.330
I was technically allowed to
be called a part of the group,

00:08:43.330 --> 00:08:45.950
but never, like never fit.

00:08:45.950 --> 00:08:48.480
And I was always a loner,
and I was always on my own

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:51.200
because those girls would
want to get together

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:54.670
and I read "16 Magazine" and
go through wedding magazines

00:08:54.670 --> 00:08:59.180
and talk crap about other
girls and probably boys,

00:08:59.180 --> 00:09:01.390
and I just couldn't go there.

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:02.420
I couldn't get to it.

00:09:02.420 --> 00:09:05.765
I was busy writing
"The Squickerwonkers."

00:09:05.765 --> 00:09:07.140
MARK DOUGLAS: So
this wasn't just

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:09.020
something you pulled
out of a drawer, that

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:11.930
was like part of
it was made, but it

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:13.180
wasn't in like limerick style.

00:09:13.180 --> 00:09:15.096
EVANGELINE LILLY: It
wasn't in limerick style,

00:09:15.096 --> 00:09:16.040
but it was poetry.

00:09:16.040 --> 00:09:20.510
In fact, at EvangelineLilly.com,
the original poem

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:22.744
is posted because it's so weird.

00:09:22.744 --> 00:09:25.160
I was actually preparing-- I'm
doing a book tour right now

00:09:25.160 --> 00:09:25.610
for the book.

00:09:25.610 --> 00:09:27.070
MARK DOUGLAS: As
we speak right now.

00:09:27.070 --> 00:09:27.270
EVANGELINE LILLY: As we speak.

00:09:27.270 --> 00:09:27.660
Literally.

00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:27.930
This is it.

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:28.750
TODD WOMACK: This is it.

00:09:28.750 --> 00:09:29.250
Yeah.

00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:30.780
EVANGELINE LILLY:
And I kept sort

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:32.640
of preparing for these
readings I was going

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:35.400
to do with these kids,
and it was so strange

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:37.650
because every time I would
prepare what would come out

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:40.800
of my mouth and out of my
mind was the original poem.

00:09:40.800 --> 00:09:44.040
It gets so ingrained in my
mind, it's so much the original

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:46.617
that it's the one that
I keep coming back to.

00:09:46.617 --> 00:09:48.200
So I posted it on
my website because I

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:49.616
thought it would
be fun for people

00:09:49.616 --> 00:09:51.110
to see the evolution
of the story.

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:52.950
MARK DOUGLAS: And did
it really come out,

00:09:52.950 --> 00:09:55.580
I mean, do you feel
confident, like does

00:09:55.580 --> 00:10:00.830
is a really look like you
always imagined it or better?

00:10:00.830 --> 00:10:01.890
EVANGELINE LILLY: Better.

00:10:01.890 --> 00:10:02.860
Weirder.

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:03.525
Creepier.

00:10:03.525 --> 00:10:04.660
TODD WOMACK: So yeah.

00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:06.930
Starting there, how
about your partnership

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:09.320
with Johny Fraser-Allen
who illustrated the book.

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:11.060
He's like a Weta Workshop guy.

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:11.560
Right?

00:10:11.560 --> 00:10:14.492
And that's who does all the
effects, physical and digital.

00:10:14.492 --> 00:10:16.200
EVANGELINE LILLY:
These people are geeks.

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:17.723
They know who Weta Workshop is.

00:10:17.723 --> 00:10:17.798
TODD WOMACK: Yeah.

00:10:17.798 --> 00:10:17.874
Right.

00:10:17.874 --> 00:10:18.374
Do you?

00:10:18.374 --> 00:10:19.070
Do you?

00:10:19.070 --> 00:10:20.250
MARK DOUGLAS: I feel
an hour here, lady.

00:10:20.250 --> 00:10:21.530
EVANGELINE LILLY: She's
like, I'm not that geeky, OK?

00:10:21.530 --> 00:10:21.913
MARK DOUGLAS: "Lord
of the Rings."

00:10:21.913 --> 00:10:23.950
They do all the "Lord
of the Rings" stuff.

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:27.640
TODD WOMACK: You need a
period-accurate crossbow,

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:29.344
call up the Weta Workshop.

00:10:29.344 --> 00:10:31.510
So he was working there,
and you guys were obviously

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:33.670
spending time together
because of "The Hobbit

00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:33.990
or what happened?

00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:34.720
EVANGELINE LILLY: No.

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:36.110
It didn't quite work that way.

00:10:36.110 --> 00:10:40.390
I was at Weta Workshop, so
Weta Workshop works similarly

00:10:40.390 --> 00:10:42.620
to Google in the
sort of 20% notion.

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:44.504
They really encourage
their artists

00:10:44.504 --> 00:10:46.670
to pursue their own passions
and their own projects,

00:10:46.670 --> 00:10:48.330
and they sort of
facilitate that.

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:51.250
And I was walking around this
incredibly-creative, inspiring

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:53.939
building, sort of like being on
the Google campus where people

00:10:53.939 --> 00:10:55.980
come here probably, I'm
sure you're used to this,

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:56.985
and they're like, oh, my god.

00:10:56.985 --> 00:10:58.693
I would want to work
somewhere like this.

00:10:58.693 --> 00:10:59.600
This is amazing.

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:00.330
And that was me.

00:11:00.330 --> 00:11:01.829
I was that obnoxious
person at Weta.

00:11:01.829 --> 00:11:03.820
I just being like
this is incredible.

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:07.750
It's this creativity factory,
and I'm a creative person,

00:11:07.750 --> 00:11:09.990
and I've always wanted
to create my own things.

00:11:09.990 --> 00:11:11.489
And that was one
of the tough things

00:11:11.489 --> 00:11:16.342
about being an actor was, like
I'm not good at being the one

00:11:16.342 --> 00:11:18.300
that someone says, do
this and then I go do it.

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:21.420
I'm better at saying, do this.

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:23.520
So I just wanted to create
something of my own,

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:25.660
and I've been dreaming
about and claiming

00:11:25.660 --> 00:11:28.480
that I was going to
become a writer for about,

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:30.982
at that point, three years
since around the last season

00:11:30.982 --> 00:11:32.940
of "Lost," saying this
is what I'm going to do.

00:11:32.940 --> 00:11:34.184
I'm going to go be a writer.

00:11:34.184 --> 00:11:35.600
But man, like just
going and being

00:11:35.600 --> 00:11:37.960
a writer is a lot harder
than it might seem,

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:40.852
so I showed the head of Weta
Workshop, Richard Taylor,

00:11:40.852 --> 00:11:42.560
some of my children's
storybooks and said

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:44.240
is there any illustrators
in this building who

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:46.050
might be interested
in partnering with me.

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:48.133
And Johnny fell in love
with "The Squickerwonkers"

00:11:48.133 --> 00:11:49.700
and created this
concept painting

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:51.910
with these marionette puppets.

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:56.050
And I was like, they were not
originally marionette puppets.

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:58.447
Originally, all I knew was
they were human but not human,

00:11:58.447 --> 00:12:00.280
and I knew they were a
bit creepy and weird.

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:03.450
But he brought the wagon,
he brought the puppets,

00:12:03.450 --> 00:12:06.050
he brought the teddy, he
brought all this stuff

00:12:06.050 --> 00:12:08.280
to the table that
enhanced, and just

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:10.030
it sort of felt
like what I didn't

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:12.770
know I was holding in my
brain came out of his hand.

00:12:12.770 --> 00:12:14.480
It was incredible.

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:15.050
MARK DOUGLAS: So
should we tell people

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:16.591
a little bit about
what the story is.

00:12:16.591 --> 00:12:20.120
It's basically a
kind of bratty girl

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:23.860
who comes across these
marionette characters

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:27.310
and they sort of teach her
a lesson-- spoiler alert--

00:12:27.310 --> 00:12:29.072
and turn her into one of them.

00:12:29.072 --> 00:12:30.030
EVANGELINE LILLY: Whoa.

00:12:30.030 --> 00:12:30.570
Spoiler alert.

00:12:30.570 --> 00:12:30.970
MARK DOUGLAS: That's
a big spoiler.

00:12:30.970 --> 00:12:31.640
EVANGELINE LILLY: Oh, my god.

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:32.190
That's it.

00:12:32.190 --> 00:12:33.260
That's the end.

00:12:33.260 --> 00:12:36.511
No need to buy the
book now, guys.

00:12:36.511 --> 00:12:38.010
MARK DOUGLAS: You can buy them.

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:39.220
It's over there at
the end, by the way.

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:41.386
EVANGELINE LILLY: So it's
clearly a cautionary tale,

00:12:41.386 --> 00:12:43.760
but I'm always emphasizing
that it's intentionally

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:45.520
a modern-day cautionary tale.

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:47.660
In that the old
cautionary tales,

00:12:47.660 --> 00:12:50.810
just programmed into kids'
minds this polarized worldview

00:12:50.810 --> 00:12:52.440
that there's an us and a them.

00:12:52.440 --> 00:12:54.269
There's bad guys and good guys.

00:12:54.269 --> 00:12:55.810
And you want to be
with the good guys

00:12:55.810 --> 00:12:59.180
so you can go kill all the bad
guys, or punish the bad guys,

00:12:59.180 --> 00:13:01.347
or not associate with them
and exclude the bad guys.

00:13:01.347 --> 00:13:03.304
TODD WOMACK: Let them
hang out with your group,

00:13:03.304 --> 00:13:04.587
but not in the inner circle.

00:13:04.587 --> 00:13:05.420
MARK DOUGLAS: Right.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:05.670
Right.

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:06.500
EVANGELINE LILLY: I got you.

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:08.080
MARK DOUGLAS: I see
where this came from.

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:08.563
EVANGELINE LILLY:
You got my number.

00:13:08.563 --> 00:13:09.500
You got my number.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:10.850
I'm just getting back
at all the popular--

00:13:10.850 --> 00:13:11.070
MARK DOUGLAS: It's
all coming together.

00:13:11.070 --> 00:13:12.778
EVANGELINE LILLY:
--girls with this book.

00:13:14.882 --> 00:13:16.340
Essentially what
I wanted to do was

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:19.910
to reprogram kids to realize
no, nobody's perfect.

00:13:19.910 --> 00:13:20.790
Nobody's all good.

00:13:20.790 --> 00:13:21.900
Nobody's all bad.

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:24.345
We've all got a bit
of vice within us,

00:13:24.345 --> 00:13:26.360
and we've all got some
great qualities about us.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:28.790
And it's all about, first
of all, accepting and loving

00:13:28.790 --> 00:13:32.420
yourself as you are, which
the protagonist of this series

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:35.250
is the Squickerwonkers
who are extremely flawed,

00:13:35.250 --> 00:13:37.280
sort of creepy,
weird-looking puppets.

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:41.290
So having heroes who don't
look typically like heroes,

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:44.570
but then also remembering
and teaching children

00:13:44.570 --> 00:13:46.760
that there are consequences
to your actions

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:49.430
and so understanding
yourself and knowing yourself

00:13:49.430 --> 00:13:51.740
on both sides, the
dark and the light,

00:13:51.740 --> 00:13:54.860
is how you sort of can
live a happier life

00:13:54.860 --> 00:13:59.770
and not befall the sort
of end that befalls Selma.

00:13:59.770 --> 00:14:01.680
So I just think I
look around me and I

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:05.500
see a lot of entitled,
disillusioned teenagers.

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:06.040
Oh, yeah.

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:07.190
You guys know.

00:14:07.190 --> 00:14:08.574
MARK DOUGLAS: Teenagers.

00:14:08.574 --> 00:14:09.990
EVANGELINE LILLY:
And I think part

00:14:09.990 --> 00:14:12.110
of that is because they were
taught in their storybooks

00:14:12.110 --> 00:14:13.760
that if you're a good person,
life turns up perfectly,

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:16.450
and everything is great in your
world, and that's not real.

00:14:16.450 --> 00:14:19.070
And they were also not told
that good people can have flaws.

00:14:19.070 --> 00:14:21.403
There's just a lot of things
missing in the programming,

00:14:21.403 --> 00:14:24.470
and I think that that's
one of the reasons why

00:14:24.470 --> 00:14:28.590
if something bad happens
to them, it's like-- me?

00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:29.577
I'm a good person.

00:14:29.577 --> 00:14:30.660
That can't happened to me.

00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:32.186
That's not right.

00:14:32.186 --> 00:14:32.980
MARK DOUGLAS: Yeah.

00:14:32.980 --> 00:14:34.012
EVANGELINE LILLY: Yeah.

00:14:34.012 --> 00:14:36.470
MARK DOUGLAS: You just go around
telling kids shit happens.

00:14:36.470 --> 00:14:38.230
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Shit happens, dude.

00:14:38.230 --> 00:14:39.702
Life's tough.

00:14:39.702 --> 00:14:41.410
The sooner you wake
up to it, the better.

00:14:41.410 --> 00:14:42.270
MARK DOUGLAS: Yeah.

00:14:42.270 --> 00:14:44.810
The one part that really kind
of creeps me out about this

00:14:44.810 --> 00:14:47.620
is, they all have
coins for our eyes.

00:14:47.620 --> 00:14:49.880
There's something
really odd about that.

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:51.730
What does that have to do with--

00:14:51.730 --> 00:14:54.290
EVANGELINE LILLY:
It's a great story.

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:56.420
So remember how I told
you I brought this

00:14:56.420 --> 00:15:00.510
to a friend and Philippa and
they helped me with editing?

00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:03.120
When I brought them the
Illustrated version,

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:05.467
Philippa almost peed
pants her pants,

00:15:05.467 --> 00:15:07.550
not from excitement, from
stress because she said,

00:15:07.550 --> 00:15:08.299
you can't do this.

00:15:08.299 --> 00:15:09.612
You can make this book.

00:15:09.612 --> 00:15:11.320
Everyone's going to
think it's "Coraline"

00:15:11.320 --> 00:15:14.520
because all these puppets
had buttons for eyes.

00:15:14.520 --> 00:15:17.084
And I'd never seen "Coraline."

00:15:17.084 --> 00:15:18.250
I was a bit out of the loop.

00:15:18.250 --> 00:15:21.970
And so she made me go sit
down to watch the film.

00:15:21.970 --> 00:15:25.290
And so after the book had been
already finished illustrated,

00:15:25.290 --> 00:15:28.070
I mean, it was done and
dusted, I watched "Coraline"

00:15:28.070 --> 00:15:30.340
and had a conniption
because obviously, I

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:33.110
realized I can't repeat
what's already been done.

00:15:33.110 --> 00:15:34.990
So we had to find
something else to put

00:15:34.990 --> 00:15:37.340
on the eyes that wasn't buttons.

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:39.982
And of course, creative
projects usually

00:15:39.982 --> 00:15:41.940
have a mind of their own,
and they find the way

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:42.970
to the best solution.

00:15:42.970 --> 00:15:46.700
And what happened was I
throw this idea of maybe we

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:49.130
could put coins on their eyes
and then Johnny Fraser-Allen

00:15:49.130 --> 00:15:52.850
lit up and said, you realize
that in Irish culture

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:55.260
you put coins on a person's
eyes at their wake.

00:15:55.260 --> 00:15:56.560
It's like a symbol of death.

00:15:56.560 --> 00:15:58.250
And I was thinking,
that's so good.

00:15:58.250 --> 00:15:59.000
TODD WOMACK: Yeah.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:00.670
Better than buttons.

00:16:00.670 --> 00:16:03.910
Buttons are for
losers, "Coraline."

00:16:03.910 --> 00:16:05.870
So what were like growing up--

00:16:05.870 --> 00:16:06.380
EVANGELINE LILLY:
There are people

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:07.450
in the audience who
didn't like that.

00:16:07.450 --> 00:16:09.240
There is like an
oh, don't go there.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:09.970
TODD WOMACK: I don't care.

00:16:09.970 --> 00:16:11.010
I'll get fired any day now.

00:16:11.010 --> 00:16:11.810
It doesn't matter.

00:16:15.226 --> 00:16:18.840
So growing up and maybe
after your formative years,

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:21.600
were there are sort of
darker influences like books

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:24.170
and movies that you were
into like, we were talking

00:16:24.170 --> 00:16:25.956
about some of the
ones that we like,

00:16:25.956 --> 00:16:29.050
like the original "Hobbit," the
animated series was a little,

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:30.780
especially the goblin
things, so creepy.

00:16:30.780 --> 00:16:32.280
MARK DOUGLAS: Yeah,
this looks a lot

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:34.170
like-- has kind
of a similar style

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:37.869
to that cartoon, some of the
animation in the drawing.

00:16:37.869 --> 00:16:40.160
EVANGELINE LILLY: Who wasn't
a huge fan of "Labyrinth?"

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:41.118
MARK DOUGLAS: Oh, yeah.

00:16:41.118 --> 00:16:43.170
EVANGELINE LILLY:
"The Dark Crystal."

00:16:43.170 --> 00:16:46.313
Does anyone in here--
god, it's magic.

00:16:46.313 --> 00:16:46.813
Yeah.

00:16:46.813 --> 00:16:50.490
Come on, with his bulging wand?

00:16:50.490 --> 00:16:51.970
That scared me as a child.

00:16:51.970 --> 00:16:55.770
That was the scariest
part of the movie.

00:16:55.770 --> 00:16:56.290
Who was?

00:16:56.290 --> 00:16:57.710
Michael Jackson?

00:16:57.710 --> 00:17:01.094
I'm so glad it was Bowie.

00:17:01.094 --> 00:17:02.510
MARK DOUGLAS: I
found out recently

00:17:02.510 --> 00:17:07.460
that a lot of women of a
certain age first male crush

00:17:07.460 --> 00:17:09.370
was David Bowie in "Labyrinth."

00:17:09.370 --> 00:17:09.690
EVANGELINE LILLY:
In "Labyrinth".

00:17:09.690 --> 00:17:10.024
Yes.

00:17:10.024 --> 00:17:10.730
MARK DOUGLAS: And
that's so weird.

00:17:10.730 --> 00:17:12.469
He's so androgynous
and kind of like-

00:17:12.469 --> 00:17:13.510
EVANGELINE LILLY: I know.

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:15.890
MARK DOUGLAS: He's got
like Tina Turner hair.

