and all us little
11-year-olds were like, whoa.

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:25.319
I feel something in my pants.

00:17:25.319 --> 00:17:26.880
I don't understand
what's happening.

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:28.545
MARK DOUGLAS: It's the
Bowie voice probably.

00:17:28.545 --> 00:17:28.980
EVANGELINE LILLY: Yeah.

00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:29.460
That helps.

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:29.860
That helps.

00:17:29.860 --> 00:17:31.484
And he can do that
thing with the ball.

00:17:31.484 --> 00:17:34.900
MARK DOUGLAS: You want to go
to Chuck E. Cheese with me?

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:36.882
Chuck E. Cheese.

00:17:36.882 --> 00:17:39.290
EVANGELINE LILLY: And
what about Edward Gorey.

00:17:39.290 --> 00:17:41.590
Does anyone here
know Edward Gorey.

00:17:41.590 --> 00:17:42.270
He was the best.

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:43.770
MARK DOUGLAS: So
you were definitely

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:45.850
into like the
creepy kid stories.

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:45.952
TODD WOMACK: Were
you specifically

00:17:45.952 --> 00:17:46.570
into that kind of stuff?

00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:47.360
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Not specifically.

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:49.180
It's just sort of
like across the board.

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:50.940
I mean, I like a
good "Giving Tree."

00:17:50.940 --> 00:17:51.750
Everybody does.

00:17:51.750 --> 00:17:52.180
MARK DOUGLAS: Oh, sure.

00:17:52.180 --> 00:17:53.490
EVANGELINE LILLY: And there's
nothing creepy by "The Giving

00:17:53.490 --> 00:17:53.990
Tree."

00:17:53.990 --> 00:17:54.589
I like it all.

00:17:54.589 --> 00:17:56.880
I had somebody asked me can
we do an interview with you

00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:58.890
where you basically
tell everybody

00:17:58.890 --> 00:18:02.150
why fluffy books suck.

00:18:02.150 --> 00:18:03.260
And I was like, no.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:04.984
I mean, I think
kids need all of it.

00:18:04.984 --> 00:18:06.400
They need the
spectrum, and I just

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:08.775
see that there's a lot of sort
of kitten bubble gum books

00:18:08.775 --> 00:18:09.510
out there.

00:18:09.510 --> 00:18:11.740
And so we need the balance.

00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:12.460
We need it all.

00:18:12.460 --> 00:18:14.960
TODD WOMACK: And this is the
first of many in this series.

00:18:14.960 --> 00:18:15.460
Yes?

00:18:15.460 --> 00:18:16.376
EVANGELINE LILLY: Yes.

00:18:16.376 --> 00:18:17.134
18 to be specific.

00:18:17.134 --> 00:18:18.800
MARK DOUGLAS: Have
you written them all?

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:19.430
EVANGELINE LILLY: No.

00:18:19.430 --> 00:18:21.040
I know what they'll
all-- like I know

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:23.920
the story for the
first nine, and then

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:27.920
I know the plot like the
gist for the final nine,

00:18:27.920 --> 00:18:31.800
and the reason
for 18 as somebody

00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:34.600
who worked on "Lost" saying
this was really important

00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:38.642
is because I have an
overarching plan for the series.

00:18:38.642 --> 00:18:40.100
I'm not just shooting
from the hip.

00:18:43.290 --> 00:18:44.040
MARK DOUGLAS: Bam.

00:18:44.040 --> 00:18:44.420
Burn.

00:18:44.420 --> 00:18:45.310
TODD WOMACK: You
heard it here first.

00:18:45.310 --> 00:18:46.600
EVANGELINE LILLY:
They had a plan.

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:48.974
I'm not knocking them, but I
know y'all didn't think they

00:18:48.974 --> 00:18:50.255
had a plan.

00:18:50.255 --> 00:18:52.380
TODD WOMACK: They're going
to come out of the wagon

00:18:52.380 --> 00:18:53.400
and it's 1907.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:54.970
What?

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:58.040
MARK DOUGLAS: I won't ask you
too many "Lost" questions,

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:00.840
but did you ever in
the middle of a scene

00:19:00.840 --> 00:19:03.776
go-- what's going
on? in that show?

00:19:03.776 --> 00:19:07.840
EVANGELINE LILLY:
All the fucking time.

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:09.450
All the time.

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:12.520
By the way, after season
three, they lost me completely.

00:19:12.520 --> 00:19:13.440
I was like, I don't--

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:15.040
MARK DOUGLAS: You were like,
I'm in the corner writing

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:16.010
"Squickerwonkers."

00:19:16.010 --> 00:19:17.480
And can we get her on set?

00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:18.940
EVANGELINE LILLY:
l literally would

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:20.487
come to set with
alcohol because I

00:19:20.487 --> 00:19:22.070
was like that's the
only way I'm going

00:19:22.070 --> 00:19:23.270
to make sense of this scene.

00:19:23.270 --> 00:19:25.306
I get a little lips--
a little loopy.

00:19:25.306 --> 00:19:26.055
MARK DOUGLAS: Wow.

00:19:26.055 --> 00:19:27.850
We're getting all kinds of dirt.

00:19:27.850 --> 00:19:29.250
I mean we both love--

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:30.340
EVANGELINE LILLY: It's
an adult audience, right?

00:19:30.340 --> 00:19:31.450
MARK DOUGLAS: I mean,
we both love that show.

00:19:31.450 --> 00:19:32.820
We stuck with it
to the very end.

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:33.940
EVANGELINE LILLY: Thank you.

00:19:33.940 --> 00:19:35.100
Thank you for sticking with us.

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:36.280
MARK DOUGLAS: My wife
was like after what

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:38.071
happened with Vincent,
but didn't Vincent--

00:19:38.071 --> 00:19:40.300
he was upended at
the end, right?

00:19:40.300 --> 00:19:40.800
Oh, no.

00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:42.600
I said I wasn't going to
go on a "Lost" rampage.

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:43.310
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Your wife particularly

00:19:43.310 --> 00:19:44.600
wants to know about Vincent.

00:19:44.600 --> 00:19:47.219
I mean, of all the
questions she could ask me,

00:19:47.219 --> 00:19:49.010
she wants to know what
happened to Vincent?

00:19:49.010 --> 00:19:50.218
MARK DOUGLAS: She likes dogs.

00:19:50.218 --> 00:19:51.720
I don't know.

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:52.220
OK.

00:19:52.220 --> 00:19:56.220
Back to "The Squickerwonkers."

00:19:56.220 --> 00:19:58.650
So when you write
a children's book,

00:19:58.650 --> 00:20:01.090
do you consult with
child psychologists

00:20:01.090 --> 00:20:03.310
or just kind of go for it?

00:20:03.310 --> 00:20:06.660
Because some of our
videos on our channel

00:20:06.660 --> 00:20:09.810
involve puppets and stuff
that kind of looks like a kid

00:20:09.810 --> 00:20:11.920
might want to watch that,
and then the next thing

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:13.836
you know, the puppet
will be like doing drugs,

00:20:13.836 --> 00:20:16.570
and we're like is this-- not
that any of the Squickerwonkers

00:20:16.570 --> 00:20:17.070
do drugs.

00:20:17.070 --> 00:20:18.778
EVANGELINE LILLY: One
of them does smoke,

00:20:18.778 --> 00:20:20.260
and I got a lot
of flack for that.

00:20:20.260 --> 00:20:22.967
MARK DOUGLAS: So do you
worry about that stuff?

00:20:22.967 --> 00:20:25.050
EVANGELINE LILLY: You know,
if I worried about it,

00:20:25.050 --> 00:20:26.890
this would not exist.

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:30.890
I'm tell you, everybody told
me, everybody told me no.

00:20:30.890 --> 00:20:32.246
Nobody would publish this book.

00:20:32.246 --> 00:20:33.620
People were like,
we're not going

00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:35.076
near that with a 10-foot pole.

00:20:35.076 --> 00:20:39.050
I had a really big publisher
outright tell me not like,

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:43.620
in my opinion, or for this
particular publishing company,

00:20:43.620 --> 00:20:46.660
it was outright, you
will not be successful.

00:20:46.660 --> 00:20:48.180
That book won't sell.

00:20:48.180 --> 00:20:52.306
And I just thought, I
think I'm on to something.

00:20:52.306 --> 00:20:55.420
This has got to
be good if people

00:20:55.420 --> 00:20:58.360
have such an extreme
reaction to it.

00:20:58.360 --> 00:21:02.266
So no, I didn't consult
any child psychologists.

00:21:02.266 --> 00:21:04.932
TODD WOMACK: That was
his question, by the way.

00:21:04.932 --> 00:21:06.522
MARK DOUGLAS: No,
I'm just curious.

00:21:06.522 --> 00:21:07.980
EVANGELINE LILLY:
But I did explore

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:10.230
a lot of the psychology
of childhood,

00:21:10.230 --> 00:21:13.310
and I call it a
playground drama because I

00:21:13.310 --> 00:21:16.950
think we forget that the
scariest people on earth

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:17.570
are children.

00:21:17.570 --> 00:21:20.070
"Lord of the Flies" might be
the scariest story in the world

00:21:20.070 --> 00:21:21.876
because kids are crazy.

00:21:21.876 --> 00:21:23.750
They don't have any
sense of right and wrong.

00:21:23.750 --> 00:21:25.416
They don't have any
sense of boundaries,

00:21:25.416 --> 00:21:27.470
and they just like
attack each other

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:29.690
on the playground for
absolutely no reason.

00:21:29.690 --> 00:21:33.010
But adults are never
talking to kids

00:21:33.010 --> 00:21:34.840
about all that
craziness and darkness

00:21:34.840 --> 00:21:36.430
that they deal
with day in and day

00:21:36.430 --> 00:21:39.112
out with each other in their
social circles, and their lost.

00:21:39.112 --> 00:21:41.570
They're left to sort of navigate
those waters on their own.

00:21:41.570 --> 00:21:44.070
And so I did think a ton
about child psychology

00:21:44.070 --> 00:21:45.535
when I was writing the book.

00:21:45.535 --> 00:21:49.520
TODD WOMACK: And when
you go into this place

00:21:49.520 --> 00:21:53.840
where you're writing these
books-- I know you have a child

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:55.870
and you have a lot of
projects and so forth.

00:21:55.870 --> 00:21:59.230
Where do you go, like
physically and emotionally

00:21:59.230 --> 00:22:01.656
to like work on these?

00:22:01.656 --> 00:22:05.620
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Because I am a mom,

00:22:05.620 --> 00:22:08.460
I don't go where I would
probably otherwise, go

00:22:08.460 --> 00:22:10.770
and I think otherwise I
would like go on a trip,

00:22:10.770 --> 00:22:13.560
or I would go to some beautiful
location day in and day out

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:14.510
and be doing it there.

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:17.240
Instead, I work from home.

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:18.870
I have a home office.

00:22:18.870 --> 00:22:19.730
It's beautiful.

00:22:19.730 --> 00:22:22.350
I mean, it overlooks a jungle,
and it's very inspiring,

00:22:22.350 --> 00:22:24.220
and it's lovely.

00:22:24.220 --> 00:22:26.500
But my son regularly
through the day

00:22:26.500 --> 00:22:28.350
comes pitter-pattering
up the stairs

00:22:28.350 --> 00:22:29.730
and comes mommy do you
want to play with me,

00:22:29.730 --> 00:22:32.271
and we talk and we have a moment
and then he goes away again.

00:22:32.271 --> 00:22:34.850
And the nice thing is that
he has this really delusional

00:22:34.850 --> 00:22:37.660
concept that everybody has two
parents at home all the time.

00:22:37.660 --> 00:22:39.810
Because he has a
stay-at-home dad, and he's

00:22:39.810 --> 00:22:42.160
very, very fortunate
in that way.

00:22:42.160 --> 00:22:44.900
So that's one of the ways
that I kind of am juggling it

00:22:44.900 --> 00:22:48.030
all is that I work from home
so that I'm also very present

00:22:48.030 --> 00:22:50.960
for my son even though I'm
working ridiculously hard.

00:22:50.960 --> 00:22:52.170
TODD WOMACK: You're writing
a demented children's book

00:22:52.170 --> 00:22:52.900
in the other room.

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:54.650
EVANGELINE LILLY: By
the way, he loves it.

00:22:54.650 --> 00:22:56.430
He's three and a
half, and he loves it.

00:22:56.430 --> 00:22:56.790
MARK DOUGLAS: That's great.

00:22:56.790 --> 00:22:58.341
I really think it's a fun book.

00:22:58.341 --> 00:22:59.965
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Like, when she gets--

00:22:59.965 --> 00:23:02.050
as soon as she turns into
the puppet at the end

00:23:02.050 --> 00:23:04.932
and then the curtain closes in a
sort of morbid way of like they

00:23:04.932 --> 00:23:07.390
end it with like the curtain
closes, and you're like, what?

00:23:07.390 --> 00:23:07.770
That's it?

00:23:07.770 --> 00:23:08.340
She's gone.

00:23:08.340 --> 00:23:10.970
There's like a rat
dusting the stage.

00:23:10.970 --> 00:23:13.270
And my son, it's
his favorite page.

00:23:13.270 --> 00:23:15.130
It's nothing but a
rat dusting the page,

00:23:15.130 --> 00:23:18.040
but it's like she got locked.

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:18.700
Yeah.

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:20.280
Because he gets
locked in his room

00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:22.912
all the time for
throwing tantrums.

00:23:22.912 --> 00:23:23.870
TODD WOMACK: All right.

00:23:23.870 --> 00:23:25.920
Is there a little piece you in
any of the characters, maybe

00:23:25.920 --> 00:23:26.530
the main character?

00:23:26.530 --> 00:23:27.460
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Everyone asked that.

00:23:27.460 --> 00:23:28.150
Everyone always asks me that.

00:23:28.150 --> 00:23:29.130
TODD WOMACK: No,
when you were young.

00:23:29.130 --> 00:23:29.700
EVANGELINE LILLY: It's fair.

00:23:29.700 --> 00:23:30.620
It's a fair question.

00:23:30.620 --> 00:23:33.120
Everything I write now by the
way, everything I write now,

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:34.600
I am the protagonist.

00:23:34.600 --> 00:23:36.800
I am fully self-involved
in that way,

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:39.380
but this one I wrote before the
self-involvement settled in.

00:23:39.380 --> 00:23:41.580
I was too young, and
it isn't really me,

00:23:41.580 --> 00:23:45.490
but my favorite character
is Greer the Greedy

00:23:45.490 --> 00:23:46.460
because she's bonkers.

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:48.810
I mean, she's just nuts,
and I love nuts people.

00:23:48.810 --> 00:23:51.680
In fact, that was a note
that I got for my publisher.

00:23:51.680 --> 00:23:54.510
In the book, it actually
says that she's crazy,

00:23:54.510 --> 00:23:56.250
and they were like,
you can't say that.

00:23:56.250 --> 00:23:57.041
You can't say that.

00:23:57.041 --> 00:23:59.030
That's politically
incorrect because you

00:23:59.030 --> 00:24:01.220
don't talk about crazy
people because there

00:24:01.220 --> 00:24:02.649
are actual crazy
people out there.

00:24:02.649 --> 00:24:03.440
I was like, I know.

00:24:03.440 --> 00:24:06.000
I have so many in my family.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.326
That's why I want
to talk about them.

00:24:08.326 --> 00:24:10.522
MARK DOUGLAS: If you
were a Squickerwonker,

00:24:10.522 --> 00:24:11.480
what would you name be.

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:15.127
There's a lot of alliteration,
Papa the Proud, Mama the Mean.

00:24:15.127 --> 00:24:16.960
EVANGELINE LILLY: If I
was a Squickerwonker,

00:24:16.960 --> 00:24:22.211
I would be Sally
the Self-involved.

00:24:22.211 --> 00:24:24.012
MARK DOUGLAS: Todd,
what about you?

00:24:24.012 --> 00:24:25.220
TODD WOMACK: Todd the Turtle.

00:24:25.220 --> 00:24:25.640
I don't know.

00:24:25.640 --> 00:24:26.510
EVANGELINE LILLY: Turtle?

00:24:26.510 --> 00:24:26.825
TODD WOMACK: Slow.

00:24:26.825 --> 00:24:27.690
EVANGELINE LILLY:
That's not a vice.

00:24:27.690 --> 00:24:29.760
TODD WOMACK: Slow and lazy,
and I like lettuce a lot.

00:24:29.760 --> 00:24:30.570
MARK DOUGLAS: Yeah.

00:24:30.570 --> 00:24:32.900
I think maybe like
Mark the Motionless.

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:34.540
We both have a similar problem.

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:37.390
EVANGELINE LILLY: They're
emphasizing their laziness.

00:24:37.390 --> 00:24:39.830
TODD WOMACK: On that note,
we do have a couple of mics

00:24:39.830 --> 00:24:42.865
out here, guys, and if you
want to ask a question,

00:24:42.865 --> 00:24:44.490
feel free to approach
one of those mics

00:24:44.490 --> 00:24:46.810
and we'll call on you
when it's your turn.

00:24:46.810 --> 00:24:51.615
In the audio book, I noticed
does it ever go full-on song?

00:24:51.615 --> 00:24:53.170
EVANGELINE LILLY:
Not full-on song.

00:24:53.170 --> 00:24:55.211
There are moments where
the Squickerwonkers start

00:24:55.211 --> 00:24:58.060
humming out of tune because
they can't sing very well.

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:00.640
But no, I mean, there
is an audio book

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:03.790
that will be exclusively
for sale on audible.com,

00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:06.363
well not exclusively on
audible, because they've put it

00:25:06.363 --> 00:25:09.740
on all different platforms
like iTunes and Amazon.

00:25:09.740 --> 00:25:11.290
But there will be
an interactive book

00:25:11.290 --> 00:25:12.947
exclusively for
sale on iTunes where

00:25:12.947 --> 00:25:15.030
there will be little
interactive elements for kids

00:25:15.030 --> 00:25:18.860
like you can change the sepia
images in the book to color

00:25:18.860 --> 00:25:21.932
or maybe little
bits of animation.

00:25:21.932 --> 00:25:23.390
There's a little
pop-up video by me

00:25:23.390 --> 00:25:26.180
and the Illustrator at the end
where I kind of help parents

00:25:26.180 --> 00:25:28.960
figure out how to talk to their
kids about this crazy book

00:25:28.960 --> 00:25:31.300
because I think they'll be
a bit at a loss at the end

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:32.510
when their child says, what?

00:25:32.510 --> 00:25:33.660
And they go, I don't know.

00:25:33.660 --> 00:25:35.740
Let's not read it again.

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:38.000
So there's a video there to
help sort of guide parents

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:39.100
through that conversation.

00:25:39.100 --> 00:25:41.500
By the way, speaking of
having to read it over

00:25:41.500 --> 00:25:44.460
and over and over, again
that was one of our goals.

00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:46.490
Johnny and I when we set
out to make this book,

00:25:46.490 --> 00:25:49.780
we were like, OK, how many
parents dread reading time

00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:52.040
with their kids because
they're like I'm

00:25:52.040 --> 00:25:56.990
going to have to read where
is spot for the 700th time,

00:25:56.990 --> 00:25:58.180
and I'm over it.

00:25:58.180 --> 00:26:00.479
So we were like, we've got
to make a book that even

00:26:00.479 --> 00:26:02.770
parents would be like, let's
read "The Squickerwonkers"

00:26:02.770 --> 00:26:03.540
again, you know?

00:26:03.540 --> 00:26:07.360
So it was like appealing to
hopefully all generations,

00:26:07.360 --> 00:26:09.780
like all demographics,
parents, teenagers.

00:26:09.780 --> 00:26:12.600
My 14-year-old
niece, when I first

00:26:12.600 --> 00:26:16.020
read it to her, not because
it's really her demographic just

00:26:16.020 --> 00:26:18.260
because I love my
niece and we're close.

00:26:18.260 --> 00:26:21.092
I read it to her and she
was like, oh, it's so good.

00:26:21.092 --> 00:26:21.800
It's really good.

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:24.490
And then she got really
embarrassed and upset

00:26:24.490 --> 00:26:27.380
for a moment out of nowhere,
and she goes, wait a minute.

00:26:27.380 --> 00:26:31.990
Auntie, is this a
book for little kids?

00:26:31.990 --> 00:26:33.620
And I was like,
well, technically.

00:26:33.620 --> 00:26:36.120
But I think it's for
everybody, like for anybody.

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:36.710
I like it.

00:26:36.710 --> 00:26:37.876
I'm an adult, and I like it.

00:26:37.876 --> 00:26:41.320
She was like, I was so
embarrassed for a minute

00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:44.610
because I really like
it, and I really want it.

00:26:44.610 --> 00:26:45.715
I was like awesome.

00:26:45.715 --> 00:26:46.340
That was great.

00:26:46.340 --> 00:26:47.381
TODD WOMACK: It's $14.95.

00:26:47.381 --> 00:26:49.650
MARK DOUGLAS: I think it's
nice that you give kids

00:26:49.650 --> 00:26:55.340
credit to sort of grasp some
of these concepts of like,

00:26:55.340 --> 00:26:57.250
the main character,
she's not all bad,

00:26:57.250 --> 00:26:58.875
and the Squickerwonkers
aren't all bad,

00:26:58.875 --> 00:26:59.980
and they're not all good.

00:26:59.980 --> 00:27:02.830
I mean, I know my mom let
me read Stephen King when

00:27:02.830 --> 00:27:06.040
I was a kid just because she
was happy that I was reading

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:11.850
anything, and I'm pretty
disturbed because of it,

00:27:11.850 --> 00:27:12.690
but I do read.

00:27:12.690 --> 00:27:15.820
EVANGELINE LILLY: Hey, you got
four million followers, man.

00:27:15.820 --> 00:27:17.020
Disturbed works for you.

00:27:17.020 --> 00:27:19.360
TODD WOMACK: So
is there any plan?

00:27:19.360 --> 00:27:23.340
I see the audio is great and
the visuals are really awesome.

00:27:23.340 --> 00:27:26.052
Is there any plan to make
an animated thing out of it?

00:27:26.052 --> 00:27:29.380
EVANGELINE LILLY: Do any
of you know who LAIKA is?

00:27:29.380 --> 00:27:30.640
Do you know the company LAIKA?

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:32.650
You know the
company LAIKA, yeah,

00:27:32.650 --> 00:27:34.650
like they made "Coraline"
and "ParaNorman"

00:27:34.650 --> 00:27:36.342
and the amazing "Boxtrolls."

00:27:36.342 --> 00:27:37.800
Have you guys seen
"Boxtrolls" yet?

00:27:37.800 --> 00:27:40.630
It is so good, so, so good.

00:27:40.630 --> 00:27:43.310
I've had conversations
with them about it,

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:45.429
and I'm not ready
to make a movie yet

00:27:45.429 --> 00:27:47.720
and they're not really ready
to make a dark movie right

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:50.962
now because they just
made three in a row.

00:27:50.962 --> 00:27:52.670
MARK DOUGLAS: You
could get Peter Jackson

00:27:52.670 --> 00:27:55.730
to make a three-hour
version of this one book.

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:59.065
EVANGELINE LILLY: A
three three-hour version.

00:27:59.065 --> 00:28:00.140
MARK DOUGLAS: No, sorry.

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:01.792
Go ahead.

00:28:01.792 --> 00:28:03.500
EVANGELINE LILLY: Hey,
man, I'm with you.

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:05.360
I was a huge "Hobbit" fan, OK?

00:28:05.360 --> 00:28:07.800
And it was supposed to
be two movies originally,

00:28:07.800 --> 00:28:10.522
and then when they turned it
into three, I was like oh, no.

00:28:10.522 --> 00:28:10.605
no, you didn't.

00:28:10.605 --> 00:28:12.200
MARK DOUGLAS: They shot
those like did 1984.

00:28:12.200 --> 00:28:13.495
I know it was a long time ago.

00:28:13.495 --> 00:28:14.100
EVANGELINE LILLY: I know.

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:14.600
I know.

00:28:14.600 --> 00:28:16.840
People were like, oh, are
you sad that it's over?

00:28:16.840 --> 00:28:20.093
I was like, well, I was six
years ago when it ended.

00:28:20.093 --> 00:28:24.710
MARK DOUGLAS: I'm like, I
didn't even want to be in it.

00:28:24.710 --> 00:28:26.970
Did you have to
audition for that?

00:28:26.970 --> 00:28:29.610
I feel like he
kind of hand picks,

00:28:29.610 --> 00:28:32.100
he has like visions of people.

00:28:32.100 --> 00:28:33.600
EVANGELINE LILLY:
This is not a lie.

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:34.390
This is the truth.

00:28:34.390 --> 00:28:37.820
He told me in 2004 he
wanted me to play an elf.

